<article>
    <h1>Us&#xAD;ing sci&#xAD;ence to check metal&#x2019;s pu&#xAD;rity</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201115/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-15"><time>2020-11-15</time></a>
        - <span>INVEST</span>
        - <span role="byline">Tan Ooi Boon</span>
    </section>

    <p>How do you know whether a gold bar is pure or mixed with im­pu­ri­ties?</p>
    <p>After all, you may think that in a ship­ment of mul­ti­ple gold bul­lion, it may be easy to slip in a dud or two to fool the pur­chaser.</p>
    <p>But the business of pre­cious met­als is safe­guarded by sci­ence and pre­ci­sion, and noth­ing is left to chance when it comes to check­ing gold’s au­then­tic­ity – es­pe­cially since each 1kg bar costs more than $80,000.</p>
    <p>DI­MEN­SION AND SE­RIAL NUM­BER</p>
    <p>Ev­ery rep­utable gold re­fin­ery takes pride in its prod­uct and, like a cur­rency note, each gold bar has a unique se­rial num­ber.</p>
    <p>That is not all – gold bars from dif­fer­ent re­finer­ies are cast dif­fer­ently, with their own length, width and height. So if you know that gold bars from re­fin­ery A comes with cer­tain mea­sure­ments, any de­vi­a­tion from them would be a tell­tale sign that some­thing is wrong.</p>
    <p>WEIGHT</p>
    <p>Gold is one of the heav­i­est met­als on earth. Its den­sity is more that</p>
    <p>dou­ble that of steel. This means that the same vol­ume of gold weighs more than twice the steel.</p>
    <p>So, it may not be vis­i­bly ob­vi­ous if some gold is shaved off or hol­lowed out from a bar, but the weight dif­fer­ence will be ob­vi­ous.</p>
    <p>A pure gold bar from any re­fin­ery at its stan­dard 1kg di­men­sions will reg­is­ter ex­actly 1,000g or 1,000,000mg when put on a sen­si­tive elec­tronic scale.</p>
    <p>Don’t ex­pect a bonus of a few ex­tra mil­ligrams – no re­fin­ery worth its salt will want to ruin its rep­u­ta­tion, let alone give you some gold free.</p>
    <p>Nei­ther would you be short­changed by get­ting less.</p>
    <p>X-RAY</p>
    <p>Gold pu­rity is tested with a spec­trom­e­ter, which emits a spe­cial Xray to an­a­lyse the metal con­tent of the bar on the spot and flag any adul­ter­ation.</p>
    <p>If the bar is made out of pure gold, the scan­ner should dis­play “99.99 Au”. Gold’s chem­i­cal sym­bol, Au, orig­i­nates from Au­rum, the Latin word for gold.</p>
    <p>SPEED OF SOUND</p>
    <p>Fi­nally, no check is com­plete with</p>
    <p>out an ul­tra­sonic test.</p>
    <p>Heav­ily gilded tung­sten has been passed off as gold in the mar­ket be­fore. Such fraud is pos­si­ble be­cause tung­sten, a far cheaper metal, has a very sim­i­lar den­sity to gold.</p>
    <p>To check against this, gold traders use an ul­tra­sound de­vice to scan gold bars’ pu­rity. As sound waves travel faster through tung­sten than gold, the scan will pick up tung­sten.</p>
    <p>With these four tests, it is quite im­pos­si­ble to make a fool out of a gold trader.</p>

